The Higgs Boson explored
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There's a theory that this boson is part of the mechanism that's responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And then there's the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model -- our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But physicists are still not 100% sure that this is the Higgs boson.
He doesn't doubt that we have a brand-new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
New data released this week at the big physics convention in Kyoto seem to confirm it, but we don't yet have all the data to be absolutely certain.
But let's assume it's the Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's see what's really going on.
There is an absolutely undeniable law in this world that two things cannot exist at the same time in the same place.
There is no way around this rule - and don't try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it has a similar law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that no two particles can occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" roughly accounts for some of their properties.
He further divides particle physics into two categories.
On one side, we find the orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow the Pauli principle.
And at the other end, there are bosons, nasty anarchists who don't care about anything at all -- certainly not this principle, which means they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups by the (incidentally, absolutely amazing) facility that is The Particle Adventure, at Berkeley Labs: mesons, which we'll leave unnoticed here, and "force particles", which are the great forces of nature that are propagating and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
It must be said, though, that these bosons are not as exotic as some might think.
If you are reading this article, it is because of a boson of unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - one of the bosons, the "force carriers".
A more stable field
It's the same with the Higgs boson, except that you have to "interrupt" another field, the Higgs field, for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it requires very high energy values to be excited, much like the frozen surface of a pond that only a very large boulder would erode.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with the input beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - to be able to develop such energy.
The electromagnetic field analogy is useful again to explain the relationship between the Higgs boson and matter.
Not all particles or materials react with an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to a refrigerator by itself.
And also, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain amount of mass, while others (like the photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Novak asks what all this research is for, what does it "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, this is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancies between observations and predictions of SM.
And many physicists literally wish they could find them, because the slightest difference could open up space for "new physics" and fill in some of the gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model is still very flawed, it does not provide any explanation of gravity (ouch!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic matter (ouch!).
However, CERN has not yet detected such discrepancies.
The response
The responses to these surveys in the daily lives of Mr and Mrs Novak are very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to think that there will be none.
Look: back in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would bring.
They were supposed to be for scientific purposes, but that's all.
The physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I've already said - the laser was originally considered a kind of "laboratory toy".
Just think about it.
And, in addition, the application may also arise from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although not originally planned by Boyle, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the LHC activities have to change our lives, but it does mean that you never really know...
