The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed with a double-key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
The content of the file also makes it possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in a public ledger of current accounts distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to record this new transaction in this ledger.
It's done by solving a mathematical problem given to the computers, whose solver, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the right to write this extra line.
This is the file-cutting phase; that is, the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
The computers "take over" this new transaction and add the number to it, only to "slice" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific impression (a value of zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then shown to be indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any editing would change the imprint.
If a user were to pay with the same money twice in a very short time (within ten minutes) for fraud purposes, the network would confirm only one of the two transactions - the other would be omitted, because each one has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this remuneration is divided regularly by two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is so limited to 21 million, but it can be divided by a hundred million, so there's room for margin...
The difficulty of the task also increases with the level of computation.
The network has had its ups and downs.
A website that provides services for Bitcoin has been hacked and the stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The problem is not the protocol itself", assures Pierre Noizat, founder of Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the same problem applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia are rejecting donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the current account book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the 'giant discounts' were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a gold-to-bitcoin exchange.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a textbook on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payments, but uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which makes it cheaper.
In addition, the user manages his identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up at retailers, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
All it takes is to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognised" by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and move towards more horizontal systems.
"It's going to take a while for Bitcoin to take off, but 2013 could be the year that matters", he predicts.
In addition, the ECB's report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are currently considered to be increased if this type of money is to succeed.
