The Tough Work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi has started another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history over the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he has decided to play vabanco.
On Wednesday, he announced that regardless of the opinion of everyone else, the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been amended many times, undermining the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal wrangles.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's polarization.
From the opposition's perspective, the president continues to be in his "autocratic delusion", continues to "break his word" and "trample the law".
But his supporters say it is a means to end the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
It is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to abandon its plan to explain the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
For the president, it's also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the country is in the midst of protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems to be convinced that Egyptians will vote for him.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people in front of an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will keep my unlimited powers", which should otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And it was in this particular atmosphere that yesterday 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most liberals were absent at the polls.
In mid-November, shortly before the Constitution was promulgated, they knocked on the door saying they had no opportunity to make their point.
Human rights defenders, civil society, or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
To make room for the new recruits, 11 replacement members were rushed in yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, articles of the Constitution were often voted on unanimously.
Commentators further commented that one of the many controversies of the day revolved around... the prayer hour, when some committee members took the view that the clocks in the boardroom were not set correctly.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and provides that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is one of their fundamental demands, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", object the liberals, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
They claim that the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which gives al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular on the issue of controlling the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
This is worrying, according to Egyptologist Sophie Pommier, because "the people who are called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This can be seen as the beginning of theocracy".
The liberals' fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next university president should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, no specific religious implication has been demonstrated.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema but university staff, many of them graduated from French schools", says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be differences of interpretation on Article 220, since the terms used therein belong to the religious vocabulary.
There is a particular reference to fiqh.
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to express themselves on this".
The text passed yesterday is being heavily criticized, in addition to its religious aspects, for the extended powers it grants to the president of the republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in their numbers compared to the previous regime.
Another controversial area: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military leaders, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, the military courts will not be prohibited from dealing with civilians, as demanded by the Human Rights Association.
These associations have expressed their doubts about the text, which they consider to be anti-freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is preserved and the offense of libel is prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are greeted by holy sites, the navel of the world, and a sea of saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of Bible truth, modern conveniences, and the unspoiled nature of the land.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
To visit the River Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God's mercy is poured out on all who enter this "bath".
And Galilee - the site of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm and filling a net.
Jesus also appeared to his disciples here after his resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Here, believers walk the Way of Sorrows, or Jesus' Way of the Cross (Latin, Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the Fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passes through the streets of the Old City and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on the hill of Golgotha - to the place of the crucifixion, to the anointing stone and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the spot where, according to Christian legend, the tree grew from which they made the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem also contains the holiest place for the Jews - the Western Wall, a remnant of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Tradition has it that people of different faiths leave notes of wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take the road vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Masada are the remains of a secret hiding place from the enemy that Herod the Great built in 25 B.C.E. for his family.
The wreck lies on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are trained in mountaineering can reach it by themselves.
The rest of us will take the cable car up this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1,600 to 2,040 meters, is the famous ski resort of Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists during the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists from the foot of the hill to this skiing paradise.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, the mountain was said to be the home of pagan gods.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting ones, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, along with some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His exhibition is widely represented by his paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Baths Museum, which presents several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of bathers and bath-worshippers from that era.
In Caesarea, the unique private museum of Ralli is worth a visit, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are strictly declined.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells one of the most dramatic stories in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in, and it's pitch black.
The stars are twinkling.
And they sound the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improving Your Health
Israel's three main spa resorts are located along the Mediterranean, Red, and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of these has a pool, a water park, a dolphinarium, and an oceanarium.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is a swimming spot during the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 70 degrees Fahrenheit [21°C] and the air is warmed to 75 degrees Fahrenheit [23°C].
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year long.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest point of land on the planet - at 1,300 feet (417 m) below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps even the ones who cannot swim afloat.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using salt water, solank, and medicinal mud that can cure health problems like dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal your nerves.
Touch the mysterious past
It is protected by the old part of Tel Aviv - the Mediterranean city of Jaffa.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mention of this city is found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it's where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists do love the narrow lanes of the towels, named after the zodiac signs.
They say that if you cling to the walls in the alley of your sign, luck will be on your side.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come from all over Israel and even from other countries to have their pictures taken.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "take" the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, please.
If you are going to Israel, you need not worry about your imperfect English: about 30% of the population in this country speaks Russian.
It is better to carry money in dollars than in euros, which can easily be exchanged for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
Buses are the main form of public transport, but Jerusalem has a rapid tram system, and Haifa has the only metro line in the country with six stations, linking the lower city with the upper.
It's basically an underground cable car.
Traveling by all forms of public transport costs 6 shekels, which can take you 1.5 hours with a change of transport.
In Israel, the Sabbath is observed on Saturday according to Jewish tradition.
From Friday evening until sundown on Saturday, work stops at markets, shops, and public transportation.
And Sunday morning is the beginning of the work week.
In many cafes, restaurants, and hotels, only kosher food is available: all except pork, seafood, skinless fish, and meals that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a wide variety of dishes made with lamb and beef, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, the traditional Jewish porridge called hummus, a variety of sauces, ground garlic balls, falafel, and fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
Yet, there are many fattening cats that gracefully "roam about according to their taste".
In the evenings, they can be seen sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The leading cats love crowded places and will indulge in any goodness.
The cost of renting a car will range from $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 a day (Audi A6, Volvo S80), depending on the make of the car.
Plus insurance - 15 bucks a day.
And it's about 15 shekels a day to rent a bike.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
To explore the country and relax, the most popular visitors were from the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
The promised land was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" announces to Moscow: the emigrants save money for the language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language tests, there are already fraudsters in the country who sell "forged" certificates
Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities are visited annually by 13 million foreign workers.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support their families back home.
On December 1, a law came into force that will require all migrant workers to pass a Russian language test.
For now, this rule only applies to those intending to work in the service, housing, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that in time, the appropriate tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the examinations will not only consist of language skills, but also Russian history and the fundamentals of law.
Language proficiency will also be required for obtaining and renewing a work permit.
The exemption applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
The law does not apply to people who successfully obtained a certificate and an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Enjoyment, conviction and protection of rights
The network of test sites will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the exam in all cities; there are already more than 160 such centers in Russia.
The initiative to promote the introduction of testing was also supported by the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law was enacted, human rights activists were able to ask the question many times in the press: what will it actually bring?
What does the language requirement change for Russians and for visitors themselves?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service responded, it would reduce the number of people suffering from "slave labour".
Many people today are talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, the chairman of the board of FMS Ruska in Tajikistan.
Their rights should be protected before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise with immigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowing the language, Sebelev says with conviction, the prospective migrant is condemned to clash with dishonest people who, under the guise of helping him, will provide him with a "pass" to the dreadful, cramped hostels where he and dozens of others like him will starve for months without food and documents and work for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"They promise them one thing in their homeland, but upon arrival they are deceived, their passports are confiscated, they do not pay the promised wages", confirms the head of the Tajik General Administration of Labour Migration MS Tolib Sharipov.
Don't give me that!
The fact that many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to Russia for work, admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get to, but they do not even have experience with the work.
Of course, it's not so much their fault as their misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get even a decent basic education.
After all, their families need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, groomed, and equipped for school.
As children reach productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
True, with regard to the language test law, human rights advocates point out one important point.
Testing will be conducted only on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't pass the exam, nor get any other official job.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers are still living in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Uninvited is prohibited"
Many of the incoming workers say that it is not easy to get official status in our country.
The reason - the bureaucratic hurdles and all the language difficulties.
Besides, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake license can be obtained quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
The Russian police know that we have essentially fake documents, no registration, and that leads to cases of extortion.
"They demand a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea", Tajik citizen Umed Shukadamov told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy yourself some paint".
On the first day of the language law, it was discovered that not only the registration documents of migrants are fake.
FMS staff have already seized several false certificates of passing a language test.
Forged documents are printed on a regular colour printer.
Of course, they did not get them for free: each of the migrants, hoping to ease the problem of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
That's two and a half times more than taking the official test: it will cost migrant workers 3,000 rubles.
The main task for the near future is to make the system more secure against corruption, so that workers cannot easily buy documents, government officials and human rights defenders agree.
In the meantime, government agencies can promise foreign workers who failed the tests the first time to take a basic course in Russian.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas that do not require active interaction with people.
