In the U.S. , fast food and supermarket workers are on strike .
A quarter of all American teenagers work at McDonald's.
In recent days, a wave of protests has been rising in America against low wages at Walmart stores and popular fast-food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether this wave will turn into wave nine or whether it is destined to disappear soon.
The whole action is supported by the unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to raising the meager wages that line workers at Walmart and the fast-food chain receive, the protest organizers are aiming to gain them a foothold in their union organizations.
At present, this sector of the economy is virtually untouched by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday", when an orgy of cheap sales swept America, enthralling millions of residents and in some cases leading to a fight.
On this day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, walked off their jobs and demonstrated along with labor unions and left-wing activists of multinational retailers whose products are targeted to the lower and middle class.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles to car batteries to vacuum cleaners to eggs to milk.
The products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That's why many low-wage employees at Walmart shop only at their workplace.
The availability and variety of goods made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
Critics say that Walmart can afford to sell its goods so cheaply in part because it pays its employees so little.
They also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of automatic trolleys or hand-held scanners.
Black Friday protesters demanded a pay raise and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the company had skyrocketed from $30 to $100 a month.
The typical Walmart employee earns $9.50 an hour, but that doesn't match the expense, employees say.
Scientists at the University of California, Berkeley, have shown that if Walmart were to raise the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
That's an average of 1.1% more than this company spends on salaries right now.
If Walmart were to shift the pay increase entirely onto the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store would cost only 46 cents more.
In a year, consumers will spend approximately $12.39 more than they do today.
Walmart's lawyers point out that the protest was held in only nine countries and the company should have caused virtually no harm.
The company's "Black Friday" sales ran from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the next day, and during that time Walmart sold about 5,000 items of merchandise per second.
In total, its teller machines processed nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
Company representative Dan Fogelman told the left-wing website Huffington Post that "less than five" Walmart employees walked off their jobs, and that the protest was "just another media sensation" organized by the unions.
"The cash register is empty!"
Protests continued this week in New York, where they were not targeting Walmart stores (which are not very popular in the advanced city, and therefore almost non-existent), but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald says he sells billions of servings, and then he doesn't even pay your health insurance and he doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage for labor in accordance with federal and New York state laws is $7.25 an hour.
Fast food restaurants are increasing this wage, but only modestly, and the average New York City line worker is paid $8.90 an hour.
Nobody in this expensive city has a lower salary.
I'm not sure how you can exist in New York City for that kind of money.
McDonald's employment will translate into almost a quarter of the American teenagers who work behind the counter after school into part-time jobs and live with their parents.
Few people see it as their main source of livelihood or plan to stay there long.
Now, I keep meeting with McDonald's employees who complain that they have to live off this money and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there's a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum that says it's irresponsible to have children if you don't know how to feed them.
Protesters, who began at 6:30 a.m. Thursday at McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and cooks at fast-food restaurants start making at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be formed in the fast-food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the formation of trade unions and punishing trade union activists with harassment and dismissal.
On the other hand, the government rarely makes their lives easier.
However, the introduction of trade union organisation in the fast food businesses is difficult for objective reasons.
One of the main reasons is the unusually high turnover of employees.
Disagreement
On this day, there were also loud protests at a number of other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The climax of the event was a rally at McDonald's near Times Square at noon, where several local Democratic politicians, most notably city councilman Jumaane Williams, spoke out, saying, "McDonald's says it sells billions of portions, and then they don't even pay you for sick leave and they don't pay you properly for your honest work!"
The protesters were also joined by other prominent New York Democrats, including mayoral candidate Billa de Blasio, who said that "we must come together to support fast food workers so they can achieve the fair wages and economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
As the New York Times described it, it was the largest event of its kind in the history of the American fast-food scene.
But only a few hundred people attended, though not all of them were employees of the fast-food chain that employs tens of thousands of people in New York.
Whether this event will become the spark that ignites the flame of a mass movement is still unclear.
