Among technology enthusiasts, virtual reality is a popular topic of augmented reality; in recent times, it has meant seeing the world primarily through the lens of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, Google presented a working model of this innovation at its annual conference, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
An interview with Sharam Izadim, head of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge Laboratory, suggests that for Microsoft researchers, glasses are a thing of the past.
The painting is a perspective manipulation of virtual objects in the air with bare hands, creating virtual public spaces.
- Can you please tell us in more detail what your research group is doing?
- We're dealing with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we're trying to push the boundaries of that interaction.
So far, humanity is stuck in the pixel-on-flat screen stage, at most sometimes just touching the screen with the finger.
We want to look five to 10 years ahead and predict significant changes in this interaction.
