There's one problem that critics often point out: there's no tactile response!
My hands are numb!
What responses is your group preparing to this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think adding the tactile senses could be the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is using the other hand as a kind of substrate for the imaging.
It's got a great way of picking up the compression!
But there are also technologies that are really focused on adding tangible to these "airborne images" -- for example, interference of multiple directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located, produces a tactile sensation, but it's still very faint -- as if you were blowing on the belly of your fingers.
There's also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you ever tried to fool the brain?
To think that he feels what he seems to feel at a given moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here's another challenge that's going to be fought for a long time -- how to make a person who's physically in a very confined space believe that they're walking in an open, virtually infinite space -- we're also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms, and also huge balls.
If the brain-deceptions become the goal, then the work is many years away.
That's what makes working in virtual reality so attractive to researchers -- a lot of stuff is in its infancy.
