But while conditions on Mars are better for life, on the surface of Venus temperatures reach 500 degrees Celsius.
Life is only possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
To answer the question of reproduction in space, scientists began with the flora.
Experiments on plants were conducted half a century ago.
Four generations of peas raised in orbit are no different from their Earth-bound relatives.
Then, the launch of insects into orbit was made - the very small fruit flies Drosophila.
In 1979, a quail egg was sent into space to observe the development of an embryo in a weightless state.
We get a perfectly normal bird on the way out.
But then the trouble starts.
"The problem is that this bird has to find support, has to stand on its own two feet and start moving", says Vladimir Sychev, the head of the laboratory at the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IBMP) of the RAN.
If they don't find support, the birds fall chaotically and make a rocking sound.
After 10 hours, the instincts of the newly hatched birds have completely disappeared.
The birds didn't respond to light or sound.
And the problem was, within four days, they were dead.
"Two times we had the birds hatched, but then we refused because it is simply impossible to work with them there", comments Vladimir Sychev on the failure of the chicken experiment in space.
The last miniarch to orbit animals was 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
But on the Bion biosatellite, there will only be beings of one sex.
An experiment was done with rats that were sent into space already pregnant.
