Head of the National Security Council: Control of the black market failed because of politicians
The Czech Republic has good controllers and good legislation in the area of public procurement, but it is lagging behind in its application.
In an interview with Aktuelne.cz, the vice president of the Supreme Control Office Miloslav Kala said:
"The law will never be perfect, but it has to be applied correctly - that's what I think we lack", Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar conclusion is also suggested by the joint audit of the Czech and German auditors.
As an example of a bad practice, he cites Peter Nečás' approach to the so-called "swartsystem".
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS will not bother the businessman with its controls - is it prohibited or allowed?
"The law must be set up somehow, and if he bans something, then even the prime minister cannot prevent the office from functioning, which has the duty to monitor and enforce obligations", Kala states.
At the meeting of the Control Committee in the Chamber of Deputies you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What was it about?
It's a parallel audit that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how public procurement is handled, followed by individual national legislation and then by practice itself.
We have combined all this, and although the control is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps "more rigorous and perfect" in our country, but the practice itself is better in Germany in some parameters.
It is thus confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but that it is necessary to deal with the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually do for you, what does it mean to you?
Such joint controls could help to stop efforts to clarify laws, reduce and improve limits, when this does not have such a positive impact.
Economy means getting the right thing at a reasonable price (but not always the lowest price) to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal activity.
But lowering the limit on prohibitions may not necessarily achieve that.
Maybe the system is so overwhelmed by paper that those who want to look for holes in the system will find it much easier to draw on than if the limit were kept higher.
You're talking about the domestic problems of putting public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there an office similar to our NKÚ, or is it set up differently?
As for the offices, just like the NKU there is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organized similarly to us, also has a college, only it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices act similarly.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but because Germany is a federal state, the Court of Auditors also have powers at the level of the individual Länder - in this respect the system is a bit different from ours.
BRH can only control federal money, represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the counties and municipalities in our country, are controlled from the level of the federal accounting courts.
What about the laws there, are they simpler than ours?
I don't like to compare it without specific data, but in some ways Germany is often called the model, but it's not always better.
Is it because they have better controllers?
I'm sure you didn't, but I'll say it again, I don't like comparisons.
But even the countries we think of as role models face a number of problems.
Otherwise, there's no benefit to them from cooperating with our agency, is there?
As for the domestic legislation, which the amendment of the Public Procurement Law meant for your office, are its effects already showing?
Since the amendment is relatively short-lived, it has not yet been reflected in our control actions.
Since we're doing an ex post check, we have to expect some delay.
We are only seeing this in the process of preparing for future controls - we have started our new 'risk detection of uneconomic' tool, through which we have run almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - where the changes will naturally be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of certain types of tendering will be adjusted and so on.
