Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, the European Space Agency (ESA) welcomed Poland as its 20th member, the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008) at a meeting of ESA ministers.
Poland started working closely with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish space enthusiasts had been flying into space before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas from his pioneering work, Introduction to Cosmonautics.
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 he won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his contribution to cosmonautics in France.
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was recognized by having one of the craters on the far side of the Moon named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway train was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown, and the details of the project are unknown.
It's not even clear whether the rocket was meant to be used to launch the thrusters or to brake them.
Information about this drezin is known only from the contemporary press.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to use rocket fire.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolczek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
From the surviving material, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, the arrival of German troops interrupted the research.
In 1937 the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were handled by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activities ended with the beginning of the war.
Further works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the post-war Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of the company is in the November 1954 issue of Problems magazine, which has four more extensive articles devoted to astronauts.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, the artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first flight was on 10 October 1958.
The 1,800-meter-range rocket was about three feet long and weighed less than 10 pounds.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledovo Desert.
The rocket was four feet long and weighed about 30 pounds.
The next developmental type was to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to track high-altitude winds.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and a launch mass of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A had a 0.4 litre capacity, the Meteor-1B had a 0.34 litre capacity and the Meteor-1C had a 0.62 litre capacity.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the development of the Meteor-2 rocket was carried out at the Leteck Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequent versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national COSPAR committee two years later are also worth mentioning.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
