Rules for balloon, banana and circus inflating
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which annually puts out a survey of the most absurd banking fees, has now decided to launch a competition for the 'most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop'.
"We were led to this by the latest event, where the EU is planning to adopt a 40% quota for women in the leadership of large European companies", said Patrik Nacher, organiser of the poll, to Pravo.
Among the absurdities mentioned is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
So far, women have been favored in life insurance rates because they are objectively less risky to the insurance companies.
"The next incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of the year.
The vote itself will then take place until the end of February 2013", Nacher informed.
Controversial EU regulations include the mandatory blending of bio-based ingredients into fuels, which damages the environment, the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, and the chicken cage size directive, which caused a sharp rise in the price of eggs this year.
The criticism was previously also faced by the de facto ban on the use of the term 'butter' or the withdrawal of traditional light bulbs from sale.
The quality bananas are supposed to be 14 centimeters long
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under pressure from business or industry lobbies, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or a group of states (even the Czech Republic is now using the threat of veto to enforce the demands of its banks).
The lobby also insisted that, for example, the highest quality bananas in the Union had to be at least 14 cm long and not have 'abnormal curvature'.
The European Commission defended itself by simply harmonising the existing non-uniform national standards that have made trade more difficult.
The EU has already relaxed its fruit and vegetable standards, despite the opposition of some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
Last year's EU regulation requiring that inflatable balloons be sold with a warning that children under 8 years of age may not inflate without adult supervision may also be a candidate to win the poll.
The EU cited US research showing that balloons are the leading cause of death by suffocation among children.
Similar restrictions now apply to children under 14 years of age when blowing into hiking boots.
Curious ideas are born at home
The rule regarding the European officials themselves is also quite absurd - anyone in an official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia, given the sensitivity of the issue for Greece, and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The BankingConsulting.com server, in cooperation with the Laissez Faire association of liberal economists, nominated for the poll, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, also the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU has set maximum quantities of food stocks that could be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded the set limits for canned mushrooms, for example, and was threatened with a heavy fine.
The survey organisers were also intrigued by the idea of paying countries to be landlocked and the idea of granting subsidies to the request for a grant.
But these ideas were not born in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped by the lack of sea.
We are asking the European Union for a refund,' said then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (CSSD) in autumn 2004.
He argued that we had a lot of grain and that as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the warehouses were full and he had to take them out.
For the Czech Republic to continue to have access to its ports, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally came to the aid of the Czech Republic by organising a tender to buy cereals from landlocked countries.
The grants were offered to municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development, headed by Minister Paul Niemiec (US-DEU), specifically to help with the application for grants from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulation is often the subject of criticism in the Member States, many experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and at the same time to make the whole Union work and develop more effectively deserve greater recognition.
The more serious problem, according to experts, is, for example, the use of EU funds for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which have been forced upon the Member States in budgetary negotiations.
The Czech Republic is also excited by the fact that, like other EU countries, it has to fight in Brussels for the right to specific labels for its traditional products, and it does not always succeed in this fight.
Although after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs have abandoned the designation of Olomouc rum, but the local rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, had to be renamed by our producers to Tuzemak.
Only products made from cane distillate and not from sugar beet may bear the rum designation.
The official list of EU products already included such products as Karlovy Vary, Požuric and Třeboň carp and Zate hops, in the company of the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from Lübeck, Germany, and Parma prunes.
The EU trademark also covers the red-headed partridge and the fire-tube.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm an amateur, Okamura says
Senator, how does a man think he's running for president?
I'm not interested in being a senator or a president.
If it works in this country without problems, I'm not running.
But I can't stand to see the country being looted for the last 20 years, with thieves running around, people getting tax rises and retirement ages.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to come up with a solution to change it.
And since I'm 40 years old and I'm a non-partisan independent, I have no choice but to run for senator or president.
You made it to the Senate, but then you went to the Castle.
Isn't that turning your back on the people who elected you?
I've said all along that I'll go into the Castle with the results of the Senate election.
I later clarified that if elected as a senator, I would run for president.
But my goal is not the function, the function is a tool to make my vision come true.
That's why I need the biggest influence and the strongest mandate.
The problem is not only that we as a nation swear in pubs and on television, but that we trample on anyone who wants to try to change.
