I've been accused of bribing journalists or being an adviser to George Paroubek.
Let's talk about your visions.
You've gone to the battle for the castle with the thesis of material and criminal liability of politicians and the return of property confessions over twenty million.
You'd have to change the law to do that.
But as president, you don't have that power, and only the Senate as a whole can propose legislation.
How do you want to handle this?
When I lobbied as a citizen to make escorting a free profession, it worked.
The problem is politicization - when someone comes up with a good proposal from the left or the right, it's purposely rejected, and that holds citizens back.
As an independent non-party candidate, I have a much greater potential to win support from all the parties in Parliament.
My preference is that without partisan boxing and dogma, I can take what's best for our country from each side and apply it.
Do you consider yourself more of a right-wing person or a left-wing person?
From a Czech perspective, I think people tend to line me up to the left.
It doesn't matter to me if it's a little to the left or a little to the right.
It's important to me that we move forward.
I don't care if someone is left or right, I want to connect people.
I will always support any public good solution, even if it is proposed by the KSCM or the ODS, and I will be just as against the bad idea.
You joke when someone says you're a populist.
But you don't prove it by what you said?
When you're creating a business plan in a company, you also have some ideal goal and vision.
And you're trying to get close to it.
Some might call it populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about are already working in the world, or have been talked about by leading experts.
But without the support of Parliament, you'll have nothing but slogans.
And that's not what you're going to do in politics for the long haul.
