I'm just saying that I'm an amateur, that I'm not a genius or an intellectual.
I'm looking for allies for my views and visions.
I'm just starting out in politics, and I'm going to try to get the majority for my program.
I'm trying to move things along myself, and if that doesn't work, I'll be out of the business in six years and back in the private sector.
It sounds a little like Okamura is supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know I can't do anything in one person, so I've been rounding up a number of famous people to see if they'd run for the Senate as well.
I went to see Radej Jančura, he refused because of the amount of work.
At least I supported the investigative journalist, Jan Lorentz, who exposed the fraudulent use of light fuel oil.
I ran with people who were really unhappy, but now I'm on the fence.
Sixty percent of the people didn't vote, and those who did vote tended to vote for the establishment.
There are only two independents in the Senate.
The people have so manipulated the Senate that it will be difficult to push through change.
I will still fight for my visions, such as the direct election of mayors or aldermen.
Are you thinking of starting your own party?
I haven't thought about it yet because I don't have the time to check the clean records of every potential party, and I don't have the money.
I don't have any money for the presidential campaign, and my transparent account is only 20 grand.
Don't you have any money?
You're talking about property declarations, what's yours?
Private assets I'd put at about $60 million.
I have a property in Prague worth about 25 million, an apartment for 10 million, another apartment for 8 million, a collection of art for about 10 million, an Aston Martin for 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb for a million, and then I have a couple of million in my account.
I got an Aston Martin, by the way, because it was my boyhood dream. I always liked James Bond, who drove around, was gentle with women, and fought against evil and bad manners.
You drive an Aston Martin, you own $60 million worth of real estate, and you don't have the money to campaign?
You say you want to change the Republic, but you don't want to put your own money into it.
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million for the campaign.
I'm supposed to go into debt?
I've already put $2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have any sponsors suggests that there's probably not that much interest in my program.
And I don't have to pay for the campaign out of my own pocket.
The cost of my campaign will be covered by what I'll be getting in my senator's salary.
But I couldn't make a living, like, I couldn't pay for my son's English school, which costs 30,000 a month.
If I was just trying to make money, I wouldn't be running for office.
So you're going to keep your business to live?
Didn't you say you'd curb these activities?
