The MVRDV architects are proof that real adventures are not just in the head - for example Spijkenisse and the recently built Book Mountain - 2 pictures
"The building seems cheerful, it looks futuristic, finally there is something interesting to see again", says Lisette Verhaig, walking along the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby large firm, says: "Of course, the house is nice".
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
They all have the Internet, iPads and e-books.
None of these old-fashioned libraries are open to the public anymore, are they?
Spijkenisse, a settlement just outside Rotterdam with no job opportunities of its own, and not worth a visit, holds a special record.
This municipality, with a population of 80 000, has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To remedy this absurd situation, a few years ago, a decision was made to contribute to universal education by building seven beautifully painted concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
The success of the education offensive was not overwhelming.
And so the city council realized that there was only one way to become the master of statistics: we had to have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, a master of wildly daring column plots and a maker of funny, often even cynical constructions, took the matter with his usual calmness and appeared at the 2003 competition with five books under his arm and a grimace on his face.
And while the committee was still looking around in awe and shrugging its shoulders, the bold Maas threw his gifts at himself in order of size and ended his activist-motivated speech with the words "Dear city people!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was finished for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office, and several adjoining residential and row houses totaling 50 apartments.
In early November, the Mountain of Books was awarded second place in the "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
The small-town shed, which could not have offered more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an extremely ugly town hall, whose white facade you would expect to be a dairy, is now enriched by a little bit of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: the reading of the Eldorado under the cheese lid.
Although there is an elevator that goes through the mountain, the real spatial and reading passion is found only when the topography is climbed on foot.
The glass interior is bright and clear from all sides, and the floor is made of burnt cabbage and the elegant street lamps clearly express the atmosphere of a public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, and a dog, and boys and girls playing soccer.
And books everywhere, books, books.
"Normally, bookshelves line the façade, and in the middle is a large, dark space that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the reader space out from the inside.
The interior of the Hill of Books is well-designed: in the center are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center, and a home technology center.
A special treat are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes walls, sometimes windowsills, and sometimes railings.
The look, the texture, the smell, it's all very strange.
Even the most experienced architects and civil engineers are baffled by the unknown building materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here", says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, to the Standard.
And so, at a farm in Frisch, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product one day.
For many years, millimeter-sized rounds of synthetic material have been used as a substrate under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and time-efficient.
Thin fabric lasts one or two seasons and then is ripe for disposal in a bulk landfill.
For the library, the fern - the first of its kind - was cut into boards four centimeters thick.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (LBP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, and heavy-duty material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a sports shoe.
105 steps to the top.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long walk, you will be rewarded with not only a fantastic view of the city but also with Dutch croquettes and figs in flower pots at the literary café.
They're concerned with the atmosphere, but more importantly, with the proper humidity of the air in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
"You may not believe it, but this house, despite the many glass surfaces, is an example of an ecological project", says Trouborst.
It's heated and cooled by the earth's heat.
Although the Book Mountain is covered with a glass dome, the sun shines in for only a short time, even on sunny days.
The wide glued wooden beams perpendicular to the glass facade serve as shading and capture much of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the work will be done by fully automatic shutters.
Spermon, an early skeptic in the IT industry, Stefan has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, whom Boekenberg even refers to as the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every citizen of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate a book from their personal collection.
The first step was to fill the optical gaps in the incompletely equipped library, which now contains 70 000 items.
The concept worked.
The shelves are completely filled.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Wina Maas.
"I think that because of our invitation, each resident now has a certain relationship with the new home.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just for decoration.
So the MVRDV has become a king in the discipline of what's known in the technical jargon as identity formation.
Spijkenisse was writing the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated.
It's the starting point for identity, after all.
Szabo: 'Germans must play a bigger role'
Germany abstained from voting on the decision to accept Palestine.
According to US-European relations expert Stephen Szabo, Berlin is balancing on the fringe of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first signaled earlier this week that it would vote against a proposal for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why would you do that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany doesn't support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he's going to support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained on the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
That was eventually adopted by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stand on important international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that they are changing their foreign policy, and that is from a policy that was so-called US-driven, towards a German foreign policy.
The situation is made more difficult by the lack of coherent and unified European policies.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they're just getting their act together, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
The foreign policy they have in France or in the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
Demonstrates a willingness to engage with national interests and positions that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. export and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from the economic interests of other great powers, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did economic interests influence the stance in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has a large presence in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
So they have to be careful not to scare the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
It does matter.
I don't want to put too much weight on it, but it's not a one-sided relationship.
But it is a major factor in German thinking.
Did Germany's relations with the U.S. deteriorate when Germany abstained on both important decisions, for example the vote on Palestine?
I think there's a lot of sympathy in Europe and even in the United States for the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a turn of events as Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
This signals that it must be considered as an international player and its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has made it clear that it is for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have existed as a result of American domestic policy always.
I think the Obama administration has a pretty good grasp of the European position.
But, of course, given the political situation there, he can't take that position publicly.
I think the differences in opinion are really not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand and its position as the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
They cannot therefore be part of a larger line and must instead push things forward from their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of its relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does it even want to take on the lead role?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a bigger role.
If you look at the European crisis, for example, whenever Germany takes on a bigger role, anti-German sentiment is created.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be acceptable to a wide variety of neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
The US influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not currently filling the vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more uncomfortable - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, DC, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America come together to study the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani are Chinese together
Armani is a world-renowned brand, Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
What is an Armani Polo?
Behind it is a name that is fully registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
It shall nevertheless enjoy protection until the actual owners of the trade mark have brought proceedings against it.
And even then, it's unclear if they'll get the law.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, which specialises in infringements of intellectual property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new case lands on my desk.
The counterfeiters need a few more letters to get their badges.
Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci, for example, and instead of Prada, they get Prada-Kny.
German companies, like the sports goods manufacturer Puma, are also legally copied in this way.
Pattloch is opening the register of the Beijing stamp office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese firm had its trademark, Zegna DF Puma, protected there, a name that also parasitizes the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are the masters of the world in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, there are several storey shops, where counterfeits are almost exclusively sold.
But Pattloch's cases are different, because he is acting on behalf of his clients against the fact that Chinese companies are officially granted the right to use a trademark that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", an affiliated brand.
This word is targeted at "Bang Dakuan".
That's what they mean by women who chase rich men.
The Chinese authorities are unaware of any guilt.
"It's hurting business, we have to deal with it", says Pattloch.
"The brand is diluted, the exclusive status is gone, the damage to the image is immense".
The financial losses and legal costs for the affected industries are in the millions, especially for expensive samples.
According to CLSA, a market research company, China is the third largest luxury goods market and the fastest growing one, with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year.
However, erasure of questionable entries in the register of trade marks can be difficult to achieve and costly.
The trial can go on for up to nine years, with uncertain outcome.
Pattloch tells of cases where the court rejected the lawsuit because the name had become a "market reality" after a long time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, the plagiarer still has to pay because he damaged his brand in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes it's the law of the jungle.
There are known cases involving graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, which had recently taken over the German concrete mix pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
