To help measure boredom, scientists developed the Boredom Proneness Scale in the 1980's.
The scale includes questions such as "Many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous", and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all".
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need for more and different external stimulation.
Teenagers, however, are generally uncaring.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said that they were bored.
Professor Larson stated that he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knows that "adolescence is the peak of boredom", which is largely because children and youths are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: "Is boredom good for you?"
Sometimes, research shows, it doesn't, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble, or abuse drugs as a way to alleviate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Nudity is the brain's way of telling you that you should do something else", said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, you'll feel good about it.
But if you watch TV, it will bring you pleasure for a short time, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he's not bored anymore, but he's not learning how to entertain himself or drive by himself, Professor Fenske said.
And "this self-control is transferred from one situation to another", the professor said.
Your child is not just learning to entertain himself but is gaining greater self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her, either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable being out of reach of the constant drubbing of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood has agreed.
"We blame her for needing to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful", he said.
What people are really looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy leisure.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated", he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise is off".
There is no manual in Colorado regarding the new marijuana law.
Nineteen-year-old Anthony Orozco, a vocational-education college student and football player from southeastern Colorado, is facing felony charges for what will soon be legal statewide - possession of several grams of marijuana and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Mr. Orozco said that one September day, he was driving with a few friends in Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, when he was stopped.
After an officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco was issued a citation for possession of narcotics and narcotics paraphernalia - misdemeanors for which each fine is $100 - and was given a court date.
"They treated us like criminals", Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
In the uncertain weeks following the Colorado vote to legalize small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug cases depends more on the place than the law.
Hundreds of marijuana possession offenses have already been dismissed here and in Washington state, which has passed similar measures.
The police department has stopped charging adults 21 and older with possession of small amounts, which will be legally permitted after the law comes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in more conservative Colorado counties have said they'll continue with existing marijuana cases, and still charge people for possession.
Meanwhile, several cities from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains are voting to prevent the opening of new state-licensed marijuana shops in their communities.
"This is moving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next", said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in the city of Aurora, east of Denver.
Even the regulators in Washington state are raising their eyebrows.
And they're looking for guidance on how to set up a licensing system for cultivation, production, distribution and sale - all by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for better or for worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it's a good guide", said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Licensing Board.
But as Mr. Smith admitted, no place or system can do more than design what might work.
"There is no real precedent by which we can proceed", he said.
The Washington law, I-502, takes effect on December 6th, which also leaves a one-year vacuum during which there will still be no state licensing system, but legal possession will exist.
And there are tangled mechanical issues that must be resolved during this time, such as how to balance a state's directive on "appropriate access" to licensed marijuana with its prohibition on hemp trading within 330 yards of schools, parks, playgrounds or child care centers.
"Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area", said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly formed research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers informing them that the city prosecutor will no longer prosecute offenses for possession of small amounts of marijuana by any citizen over the age of 21 and that the police will "with immediate effect" stop charging people for these crimes.
Chief Oates said that the police will enforce the city's laws regulating medical marijuana growers and that they will continue to prosecute drug dealers and dealers.
In northern Colorado's Weld County, District Attorney Ken Buck is taking a more hard-line view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them face additional charges.
"Our office is obligated to prosecute criminal offenses that were crimes at the time they were committed", Mr. Buck said in his statement.
The response has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County where voters have rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer charge adults with possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supports this decision, but has also decided not to dismiss all of the ongoing possession cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes", he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the arms of government and the legal system will never be easy.
And the conflicting reactions across the state to this great state green experiment revealed deep divisions among local officials.
For district attorneys, it's a "cultural barrier", said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents marijuana defendants and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They've spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can't really accept that it's legal", he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are well on their way to becoming national test cases for drug legalization.
The defense and state agencies are planning new limits on legalized sales while also anxiously awaiting instructions from the federal government, which still plans to make the sale and cultivation of marijuana a federal crime.
Marijuana legalization advocates are hoping the Justice Department will bow down.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana dealers and patients who use it that garnered attention, the federal government has mostly kept medical marijuana shops in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states open.
While drug enforcement agents are unlikely to break down doors to seize a small bag of drugs, they are likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana businesses to be allowed by the new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several Colorado towns are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments have approved a moratorium on any new marijuana businesses, although it will be another year or so before any businesses can open.
Last week, the city of Montrose in the western part of the state proposed a six-month ban, and it's likely to go into effect next week.
"We don't want to be in a situation where we're issuing a license to somebody and then we have a big federal issue", said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our people voted against this amendment.
We're looking at what the community voted for versus what the state voted for.
There are a lot of questions.
Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a Conservative".
It's not just today's college students who are being attacked for their views.
I can't remember a time when I didn't dream of going to Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother studied at what I thought was the world's greatest center of learning, a modern-day Greek-style symposium motivated by the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
And yet, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of entering Worcester College, where I was going to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed I quit because I objected to having sex with students in the next room.
Author A. N. Wilson brazenly stated that I left because I was forced to drink from beaten-up cups.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was the subject of systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my somewhat bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment, it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You may ask why I'm bringing this up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students on the center-right are suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of conservative students called for the same equal rights protections as gays, people with disabilities and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College Junior College (JCR) claim that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks, and made to feel unwelcome".
They are asking for a position on the university's Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that they can express their views freely.
Their plight was not helped by the recent BBC Two documentary Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right about student politics, which conservatives portrayed as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who drove a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and had a silver-headed cane.
At other colleges, conservative students say that they are being treated like "scapegoats" because of the higher tuition.
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told the Sunday newspaper that "leftist influence on the universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without ever meeting us".
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is "unpleasant", while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in the JCR membership's attitude toward people on the centre-right.
"It poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion as well as to the well-being of the members", he says.
During my first few weeks in Oxford, I was a one-member minority.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and cripplingly shy.
The hatred of the Conservative Party was the most fervent.
A year earlier, the university voted to deny an honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher over cuts to higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have made even Stalinists tremble with fear.
During the first few days of the first week, when the new students are interacting with each other and with the professors, I got a taste of the soup that was coming.
I found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the picking of conservative students, they willingly participate in it.
The timber-framed offices were brought in by the policy of the miners' strike, privatization and the government's resistance to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa.
My first lecture was on the translation of an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt", said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph".
I was pretty tough.
Professor Pitt, the little man with the face of cake dough, was very gallish.
"Do the Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students were giggling.
I had tears in my eyes.
"I suggest that you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, if you're not too busy with social activities", Professor Pitt growled.
I went back to my room, crushed.
I was sitting alone at dinner at school when I felt a light tap on my shoulder.
It was a sophomore named James who identified himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are", he said kindly.
Unfortunately, that's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of being a conservative is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most conservative freshmen are pretending to be Labour.
Later, at a local tavern, I made a cowardly attempt to pretend.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything that Thatcher said.
This trick has proven unsuccessful.
A first-year student in philosophy, politics and economics who (ironically) went to Eton said, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig".
You are infected.
The other students took notes with it.
I was dirty, I was dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" one asked.
They're beating each other up, aren't they?
I felt like the gays must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever have a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
I'd have to turn into a Labour and suppress my natural inclinations?
Three years before me have developed into a purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who was based on my faculty.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but for being Margaret Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speech-writers.
He was barely there.
He hated the place for its provincialism and pettyness and for its tendency to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here", he told me.
I began to commute from Oxford to my parents' London home, seeking refuge with my unbiased metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world", he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in the city of dream moods.
Even my communist friends always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes turned grim.
Try it again.
I'm sure it was a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience deteriorated.
A friend of mine, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to pressure and renounced his beliefs.
The following week, in class, when another history professor declared with all seriousness that I was "an enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Although I was blushing with shame, I admitted that my "parents had brainwashed me" and called them "old fools".
The relief was only temporary.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week for the Murdoch newspaper.
My door was locked.
I crept inside, and after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never went back.
You can call me a grinning weakling.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subjected to such intimidation and toxicity in an educational institution.
But even more tragically, it was Oxford that not only produced 14 Conservative prime ministers, but that to this day hides behind an undeserved reputation as a place of equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the occasion of the "Valentino: Master of Fashion Design" exhibition that opened this week in London, ABC spoke with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisz and other celebrity clients of the Italian designer.
Somerset House, the ancient residence of Isabella I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition by Valentin Garavani.
The designer confirmed this at the opening of the celebratory retrospective "Valentino: master of fashion creation", which presents more than 130 models of high fashion created by his atelier over the last 50 years.
"I love this castle", he says in his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story in which "il signore" Garavani is the only protagonist, but it could not have been written without his esteemed clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rare and distant world of aristocracy.
The first exhibition hall, which will be open until March 3rd, is filled with private correspondence and photographs signed by the most important nobles, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to the Greek princesses Marie-Chantal and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino exhibits these personal memories as trophies of his social ascent: from a simple tailor from the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international "bohemian cream".
There's nothing wrong with liking royals.
"At least they don't put a cigarette butt on a great carpet, like some of the great pop-music celebrities do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisz.
In the '60s and '70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an impressive host and entertains his guests with plenty and elegance.
"We were all very pleased to be invited to his Gstaad cottage", explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli and Eugenie Niarchos.
"Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet he is a star".
Valeria Mazza is playing Valentine
The charisma of the designer is not forgotten by the Argentinian model Valeria Mazz.
"It's been many years since we went to dinner with him after a show in the Piazza di Spagna in Rome.
There were 20 of us, and among us were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
Every detail of his apartment, the decor, the food, the music, everything was turned on and his spirit was felt.
He made everyone feel important and loved", recalls the top model, who began working with him during Paris Fashion Week in 1995.
"It never goes out of fashion because its designs are works of art", he concludes.
The parade of nobility
Gravani's life is not a story of obsession, but of true love reversed.
He loves people with good upbringing and better titles and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House has been rebuilt into a distinctive seventy-meter-long passageway that offers a change of role: the visitor turns into a model and walks down the aisles to observe the "audience" of dreams worn by Valentine's masterpieces such as the dress that Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume worn by Monica Vitti in "Night", or the wool and fur coat that belonged to the Empress Farah Diba.
Among the models' audience are Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria of Thurne and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria, and Sophie of Habsburg.
Naty Abascal and the designer in 2006
Many of these clients say that a first Valentine's Day is like a first love, "you can't forget it".
"I remember it perfectly.
It was pants, a shirt, a "gillette" vest and a jacket from the autumn-winter collection of 1971-1972.
It was a gift that he made for me", says Naty Abascal, one of the designers' muses.
"I prefer him to others because of his femininity and his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty", adds the former Duchess of Ferri.
"I really like the colors he uses, they make the face look a lot brighter and more sparkly.
The proportions are perfect".
Not even the princess and fashion icon Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can forget the first time she dressed Valentina.
When she was growing up in Italy, she longed to be an adult and to have the opportunity to wear one of his evening dresses...
She finally made it to the late '90s.
"I bought my first dress from Valentin for the occasion of a wedding at the castle of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress that had a skirt with a sash, a high-waisted skirt, and a top with no sleeves.
It was a dream come true", says Rodrigue d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino is lax about fashion, his passion is timeless", explains an Italian aristocrat whose life alternates between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
The Princess of Arenberg has laid out the designer's wedding dress "very carefully... because the dress is not just a dress, it is also a set of memories that they have inside".
The "King" of Fashion
The highlight of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress from her marriage to Pavel Grek in 1995.
To create this silk dress of ivory color with beads, twelve different types of necklaces, and a four-and-a-half-meter-long hem, it took four months of work and 25 "holek" (the designer's name for his sewing).
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the foremost authority on the trade press, these dresses represent the high-fashion milestone of the late 20th century, "the return of the high society clientele".
Valentino, dazzled over the years by elitist savoir-être, is now the best example of it.
Knighted as Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest decoration in Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres and decorated with the Legion of Honour, he accumulates as much honour as any of his client's husbands.
"I was always attracted by his elegance, his calm, orderly and perfect appearance", admits Princess d'Arenberg.
"I last saw him a month ago at a gala dinner at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was at the table with the Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, my great friend.
He was perfect, time left no trace on him".
If the princess says so...
The hardest job in the world: sulfur haulers in the Kawah Ijen area
For four euros, porters in the Indonesian volcano area risk their lives and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone paths.
There are people who think their work is hell, and there are people who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, they must dig to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulphur gases escape from the Earth's interior and, on contact with the air, solidify.
After he has cut large blocks of sulfur, weighing up to 150 pounds [70 kg], he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 800 feet [2,386 m] to the summit of the 8,500-foot [2,386 m] volcano, but it takes the exhausted porters more than 40 minutes to make the ascent at a torpedo-speed pace, as they maintain their balance and carefully balance their steps to avoid slipping and falling into the abyss.
They know that any slip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners at Kawah Ijen make five cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine
When they are up, they are being photographed by tourists, who are photographing them as if they were monkeys in a circus, tiring their heavy baskets to a scalar that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 6,500 feet [1,800 m].
The company, PT Candi Ngrimbi, has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian Rupees (five cents) per kilogram of sulphur.
Then he sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used to make lighters, firecrackers, cosmetics, dynamite, and even sugar bleaching.
"We usually carry 70 kilos, so we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
He takes three hours to drive one way and is destroyed at the end, but he can make 138,000 rupees ($1,750) a day.
While this may seem like a negligible amount for such an inhuman effort, it's three times what he would have earned on the field.
"The daily wage of miners here is very high, for example, for coffee harvesting, they pay 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day, and the 14-day wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", explains a porter who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2 euros) a day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as compelling as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu and took her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, shortness of breath, persistent cough, and eyes irritated by toxic gas.
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, where sulfur has already begun to take its toll, despite his face being protected by a special mask and goggles.
He has asthma, bad breath, a constant cough, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases leaking from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French", promises more than decent English.
This charming and intelligent young man, who could be a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, is doing the job of a porter.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and gets up at two o'clock in the morning every day because the sulfur keeps boiling at night and its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Through the surrounding darkness, Anto climbs into the crater and lights his way with a small lamp that he has attached to his helmet and that he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry on their shoulders baskets of sulfur from the crater floor
Although the company has a high income, it has not mechanized the sulfur extraction to save costs, nor does it provide any equipment to the self-employed carriers with such effort.
In fact, they do not even get a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of the photography surcharge, which, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) ticket, is collected by the park rangers from tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for cattle, not for people", complains Madrusin, a 42-year-old butler who has worked in Kawah Ijen for three decades, since leaving school.
He can lift up to 110 kilograms and assures us that he will keep working "as long as he can", because he needs money to educate his three sons, aged between 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here, because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns their throats and stings their eyes when the wind unexpectedly turns and traps the miners in the thick fumes that come out of the volcano, the miners are so stubborn that no one complains of suffering from serious illnesses . . . but it is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain, and shoulder injuries caused by the weight of the baskets.
At 53 years of age, the Unaik, who balances his basket on his back, can only carry 50 kilos.
Each day, he and his colleagues extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is then transported by three trucks along a steep path through the bush to a warehouse in Tamansari, 11 miles [18 km] away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because I've been a volcano all my life", Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, missing several teeth.
The eldest of his five sons, aged 30, also earns his living by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the unending misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by the human mullahs of Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the lack of children on career stress and the cost of living and education.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm a married patriot, you're my wife, and you're a patriot, so let's do our civic duty and start a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a commercial for menthol candy, but nevertheless - or perhaps because of this - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
These sentences are part of a rap that uses local allusions like "let's put the pot in the oven" to mock the birth rate in Singapore.
BBH, the advertising agency that produced the video, hopes that this ad will help them to notice the problem in a humorous way.
The agency's artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, says that he wanted to use the power of music to make people do "their civic duty".
"It's all about the Internet, so it must have been fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing our population, so we felt that this was a topic that we needed to address.
We knew that the government was trying a lot of things like promoting pheromone perfumes or having dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they weren't entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like rapping, to solve this problem".
1.2 children
The one that doesn't take it lightly is the Singapore government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
All these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leaders and strict social controls.
The fertility rate in Singapore, in terms of population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered the recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Population Bureau, says it is because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"People have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, not just marriage and family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the delay in marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decline in Singapore's birth rate.
While there were efforts within immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against population decline, this provoked resentment among the local population.
Some Singaporean websites show an open xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore's ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence.
After the election, there was a push to solve the problem through quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health care expenditures, and immigration policy, there have also been some unanticipated consequences in Singapore's case.
The government is trying to stop so many small houses being built.
It began to affect the real estate business, for example.
The Department of Housing and Urban Development has begun regulating the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments are 46 square meters and have been a great success in terms of sales.
However, there is concern that these apartments may encourage a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the developer EL Developers, claims that their "boot boxes" are selling far faster than larger houses.
"They are more popular, and they sell days or weeks faster than houses with more floor space.
So they're much better for our cash flow".
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously restricted from offering too many small houses in one project.
Too Stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could be aimed at increasing the nation's birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district suggests they won't have much of an effect.
"People are always stressed, houses are expensive, education is expensive, so many people put it off", says a young official.
"Let the others have children.
But for me, it's important to rely on my own money and time", says another, in his early 20s.
Men and women cite career stress and the cost of living and education as reasons for not having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is ultimately Singaporeans who have the final say in starting a family.
Offline privacy is private as well as online.
It's private.
According to the dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any interference".
What's privacy to someone under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the danger he is exposing himself to by posting things on the Internet that he would almost certainly not tell anyone in a normal communication?
ElPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years old who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be 'something entirely personal' on a personal level and 'username and password' on a social network.
"My biggest secret is not to go public", says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret, my mom might know about them, but not the whole world", he says.
"I put nice pictures on Facebook or pictures of us playing.
I also go there to talk to people I know.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that would embarrass someone", he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene, nude, or criminal photos or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 of his friends on Facebook and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends", he says.
Without hesitation, he says that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask, and on the latter network he admits that he doesn't know 20 people from his friends list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to this boy, none of them asked him for anything, not even an address or a phone number.
"If they press me or demand it, I simply delete it from my account", she admits.
José joined Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
These boys are no strangers to what we now call cyberbullying.
"Friendly social media user was blackmailed.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who he was", he says.
The victim didn't log off from the account, according to Josh.
"She just activated her private mode".
Then it explains a series of steps to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of people he knew in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if I didn't like someone or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate of the Department of Education and Training, believes that in order for children and adolescents to navigate social media correctly, they must understand that the main purpose of these networks is to inform.
He states: "The Internet began as a means of information retrieval, but the advent of social networking changed the rules of the game".
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate student of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital natives and digital immigrants, introduced these terms to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the age of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are still learning ourselves", he says.
She explains that it is a difficult subject "because we ask them to distinguish between what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
Also, to be environmentally prudent, at a time when what they want most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences", she adds.
She says that the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to ask thought-provoking questions.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work", he adds.
Marrielos Porras goes on to list some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or, "Would you like it if someone posted your picture like you posted a friend's?"
Do you know what other people are saying about you?
When you tag people in photos from the party, did you ask those people for permission?
And one more: does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in an online environment just as they do off the Internet.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the internet, people are guided by respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be true on social networks", he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first grade teacher, and educational consultant, explains that it is essential for parents to read the rules of social networks carefully.
"If they understand the insidiousness of each, they have a good basis for discussing with their children the consequences of setting up an Internet account.
For example, on age or what is allowed to be shared or published", he says.
Guardia feels it's important to remind children of the traditional rule "don't talk to strangers".
The South American Summit ends and the Lima Declaration is not published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the issuing of the Lima Declaration, which was approved and allegedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the 6th UNASUR Heads of State and Government, but representatives of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidential Office, who initially stated that the document would be published after the summit, said that it would be published later on the website of the Peruvian government.
They further stated that the content was made public by the Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Press access was restricted throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential meeting was broadcast in the press room without sound, with the message "confidential meeting, sound transmission prevented".
The limited information available to journalists was provided by spokesmen for some governments who were present, but not by the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of the presidents attending, which provoked the displeasure of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets, who demanded more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an email to the media with the "concluding statement" from the summit, but this is only the statement of President Humala, and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the Americas of the South-Países Árabes (ASPA) and even on this occasion, the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, despite being eagerly demanded by the press.
The official ASPA website states that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that all journalists had access to the news, but they completely blocked the flow of information.
The Summit ended, among other things, with Chile and Peru jointly committing to accept the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
President Ollanta Humala of Peru and President Sebastián Piñera of Chile met in a regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will start hearing defense arguments from both sides on Monday to hear the dispute initiated by Lima v. Santiago.
"We will obey and execute the sentence that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today in this international court", said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, conventions and international courts", Piñera added, greeting President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia this week adopted the Bogotá Pact, expressing its abiding by the international court's ruling on the maritime border with Nicaragua, which Colombia considered to be completely wrong.
The Summit was held without the participation of the Presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the recall of then President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and closing the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, which informed that 16 agreements had been accepted and activity was planned for 31 projects between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR member countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residency agreements are being extended".
He reported that actions are being supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organized crime, to improve access to medicines and low-cost internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters".
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not be a winner, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our peoples a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport connections between the different places of South America, especially the rural and border areas..., so that our countries are better connected and create new economic links", the Peruvian president said in a speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and its transverse axes from the coast to Brazil, and the other two are for better connections with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the Summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region, one that is integrated and has good neighbourly relations.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before his participation in the regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully discuss the International Court of Justice ruling on the maritime border dispute contested by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow", Santos said.
"We will discuss all solutions, none are excluded, nor a treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country", he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and thoughtful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are meeting in Mexico on Saturday, where they are expected to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peña Nieta.
The EU Defence Ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence matters.
The members of UNASUR are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chairman of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn from Europe on integration
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa announced today that the creation of a common citizenship is the goal in which "South America, in this case, really must learn from Europe".
Correa, who was attending the sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, Peru, said on state TV that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are practically one nation".
In this sense, the project advocated the creation of a South American citizenship, which is supported by the member countries of Unasur.
"We must achieve the free movement of citizens and workers within any South American country that is already taking place between the members of the Andean Community, but there are still regressive areas that want to return us to the past", he warned.
Among other things, the Ecuadorian president expressed his agreement to the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the condition that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states be reduced and that those who signed the San José Covenant on Human Rights be taken into account.
"Those in charge never commit to anything, and we South Americans sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights in Washington is funded by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he did not regret the decision because it did not betray his principles, and respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He added that at the time "there was a reasonable suspicion that Assange could be extradited to a third country regardless of the trial in progress".
He also criticized the Swedish judiciary, which asked him to be questioned on Swedish territory for an alleged sex offence, and "Swedish law allows for the interrogation to be carried out by videoconference, which could be carried out from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's physical and mental health could deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he was at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a minor lung problem, but nothing serious", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
"But his physical and mental condition is in danger of deteriorating, "because he is confined to a small space, "without the possibility of moving out into the open air.
It would affect everyone's health", he added.
President Correa noted that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London on the basis of a permit that allows him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and European courts, and stressed that talks have been held with London to resolve the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
"We don't negotiate human rights, we don't use that word in this case, but there have been conversations all along.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, as Assange's lawyer Baltazar Garzón is leading a series of proceedings before various European bodies", he said.
He said, "If the UK issues a release tomorrow, it's all over".
And if Sweden can interview Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as is readily permitted by its legislation and as has been done in other cases, this problem will be over tomorrow".
Correa took advantage of the situation to present himself as a defender of freedom of the press, making it clear that he does not tolerate "understatement, bad intentions and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
The greatest enemies of a free press are not us, the vile and perverse politicians, but bad journalists in the service of profit, coercion and blackmail", he said.
In this regard, he expressed his satisfaction that neither such journalists, "nor the bankers, nor the hegemonic countries, nor the bourgeoisie, rule Ecuador", and he said that if reelected, "he will continue to make changes in the right way and in the right direction".
President Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay's membership in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the whole "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coupism wrapped in legality", because in fact "it has destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian president also said that he considered "quite appropriate" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua on the maritime borders between the two countries now, after the International Court of Justice in The Hague ruled in favor of Nicaragua.
The verdict is not currently admissible.
"This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They must be considered in their broad outlook in order to overcome them and to be able to move forward".
He also expressed hope for a settlement of the maritime boundary dispute between Peru and Chile before the same court, expressing the opinion that "it is right for Latin America to seek an international instance if both countries commit to accept the verdict, however harsh it may be".
Regarding the possibility of running for a third term in the next presidential elections in Ecuador, he noted that he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, even if it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa has stated that if he loses the election in February 2013, he will retire from public life.
"I personally have never been interested in power, but situations as unjust as the socioeconomic poverty in Ecuador can only be remedied by political power.
My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so we have to accept this responsibility", he said.
"If I win, it will be my last term as president and then I will retire from politics.
If we lose, I'll be the same.
I've made my decision", he said.
Correa also mentioned the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
"I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who says that President Chavez had gone for a scheduled routine treatment and his return to Cuba was expected after the campaign ended.
This is not a relapse in the president's health", he explained.
The head of state of Ecuador today attended the sixth summit of the Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration in order to maintain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when his test came back positive for HIV.
"It was like being struck by lightning", she recalls, reflecting on a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "slightly soften" but apparently failed.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on himself and started to learn about it, and with such dedication, he celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is without doubt one of the longest-serving patients in the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined in 1994 after several struggles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of uncertainty, few treatment options and greater stigma.
At the time, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say good-bye to him, "because he had a cut".
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, many people are unaware of their illness and come in only after the virus has wreaked havoc with the body and weakened the immune system, and they become casual victims of infections.
Thirty-one years after the AIDS epidemic, or at least since the first documented cases, "it is a great achievement that the life expectancy of a patient who is started on treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, with this information confirmed in a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
Andrade Villanueva, an infectious disease specialist and HIV/AIDS specialist, explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008, AIDS is not a death sentence but that survival and full life expectancy depend on the degree of immune system impairment of patients diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not take drugs better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "live to 75 years without problems, if he continues to receive treatment", the doctor explained in the interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth noting that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS fell from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (Joint Programme of the United Nations on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this year as of May.
Why do people keep dying from the effects of disease?
- "I don't think the problem is in the treatment options.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in our hospital.
We haven't run out of drugs in at least the last 12 years, and the problem is that patients come in at a very advanced stage because they don't know the disease, which is the late stage of the disease".
It adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come in with some co-infection, and the only thing we can do to make a difference in the overall mortality rate is to diagnose the disease early, and therefore to offer screening tests on a large scale to all those who request them".
His proposal is in agreement with experts and officials from the State AIDS Prevention Council in the state of Jalisco, as well as with patients like Fabrizio, who came to a private laboratory to get tested just because a friend had done it, and despite his young age, had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous disease that is one of the common complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know any more.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather do three times a week", they say, but that's not my case.
I've changed for the better, I'm healthy, I'm exercising, I'm on medication".
To this day, his parents only know that he had cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sexual life, but I take care of myself and the other person responsibly", says Fabrizio, who accepted the challenge to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO journal to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested, if they're at risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, that's better, and if they've been diagnosed, let them know that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible".
This message sums up the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who researches HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that do this, "they've actually increased the condom distribution, they used to give us one or two, now they give us packages of 100 condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are teenagers.
"What do you want for it?" is a common question filled with irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacists, and health-care workers that adolescents want to avoid, says the reporter.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution, not just behind the counter, but in the dispensers of public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"It is not promoting promiscuity.
It's not even about "paying for beer and a motel", as Governor Emilio González responded to a question about whether he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
The best thing is to make condoms available to those who are already having sex", he said.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
There were 13 435 cases (12 158 cases of AIDS and 1 317 cases of HIV).
This condition ranks fourth in new and identified AIDS cases in Mexico and 13th in HIV-related cases.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are blood-borne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that some 50,000 people may be living with HIV, since for every registered case, there are four to five people who are unaware of their disease.
The judgment of the United States Court of Appeals, which does not recognise the restructuring of the debts of Grupo Vitro as established by the bankruptcy in Mexico, sets a bad precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country and solvency problem.
It seems that the corporate restructuring procedures that Mexican law allows are not applicable in the Land of the Stars and Stripes, despite international agreements.
The approval of the ruling issued on June 15 last year by Judge Harlin Halem in the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves in practice a Mexican company defenseless against the possibility of confiscating their property on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to the United States Supreme Court for the leading Mexican glass manufacturer to appeal against three of the irregularities.
For a start, while the judge in this case argues that creditors should follow the United States' insolvency law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the main proceedings provide for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, it would show a lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of multinational enterprises.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law, which is arbitrated by the American Law Institute, was created for this purpose.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the voting of the branches from the internal corporate structure, whereby the indebtedness of the parent company Vitro towards the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is permitted by Mexican law.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first to adopt this scheme.
There are half a dozen examples like Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose corporate debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Bankruptcy.
Moreover, it is true that even after the branches' votes had been counted, the creditors - who had been suing Vitro in the United States, i.e. the 'soup' funds, such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved a majority.
In the ballot, they would have got about 45 to 37 percent.
The Court of Appeal disregards that assertion.
On the other hand, the Court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008, against the background of the severe economic crisis that hit the United States.
In the meantime, the family firm of Gonzáles Sada will appeal to the Court of Appeal for a new trial, so that the trial is conducted in full, that is, with the participation of five judges, since originally only three judges voted.
If he fails, he will seek a review of the process by a higher court, in this case, the Supreme Court of the United States.
What is significant in this case is that the court omitted to mention a document sent by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae detailing Vitro's conduct under the Bankruptcy Act and pointing out that the company had taken it easy by relying on agreements signed by both countries to confront that Act with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
Moreover, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for both debtors and creditors.
A blow to both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
The overall assessment
