Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, a basketball world champion, has been involved in the indoor sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before a stroke in 2008 left him in a wheelchair, Reyes had been involved in the sport for more than 60 years, as a junior player, a player of the National Basketball League BSN, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón team in the National Basketball League, and president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
"I have played many roles in my life in basketball, including several simultaneously, such as being president of the BSN national league in the 1990s, general manager of the national team and president of the federation", Reyes recalled when he visited reporters from Primera Hora newspaper at his home in Bayamon, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house, almost entirely decorated with photographs and memorabilia from his long career, bear witness to this.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest emotion of all the guards, those that commemorate his tenure at Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or team owner.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with the team of Los Vaqueros since 1967, either as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I was out of the league for one year, 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
"Cuco" Ortiz took over the team, and he was a great leader", Reyes said.
"I remember Gene Bartow, who was a former coach here and at the time was at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, telling me, 'I have a grown-up player for you.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brings Bayamonu a championship win, Gausse will then contribute to the next one.
Gausse enjoyed the championship, but only remotely, because in 1988 he was already the president of the basketball federation.
At the time, he wanted to devote himself fully to his duties and enjoy Mincy's place in the national team.
"I remember the first time we beat the United States in an Olympic qualifier in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, but we would have had the bronze had it not been for the Canadian referee who made us repeat the final throw", Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He's one of the best, like the one who beat the Dream Team at the Olympics in 2004.
But my favorite was the national team in the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was very similar to the way we won bronze at the World Championships.
That team not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramón Rivas, Fica López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also had the youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be on the team in 1990 due to a knee injury.
The men's team that may not have been a perfect team, but that was able to win a gold medal and bring us great joy, was the 1995 Olympic qualifying team in Neuquén, Argentina.
