The actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, is best known for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series Dallas, in which he played a man who acted recklessly and was vicious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new series of Dallas, died Friday afternoon of complications related to cancer, according to a family statement provided to the Associated Press by Dallas Warner Bros.
"Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most", his family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who played his wife in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death in a Dallas hospital", her agent Jeffrey Lane announced.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, gentle and talented, and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest", Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he himself admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and Hagman underwent a transplant.
A year before Dallas aired, Hagman made a name for himself on television as a decent guy in the light-hearted sitcom I Dream of Jeannie, which ran on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
He played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a genius) played by Barbara Eden and takes her to his home to live with him.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film appearances include the critically acclaimed The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman's masterful performance in the form of the incredibly repulsive J.R. that brought him to stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities surrounding them ran from April 1978 to May 1991.
The "Who shot Ja'far?" campaign, which was supposed to raise expectations about the thrilling story of the Hangman's character being nearly murdered, not only caused a huge amount of speculation from viewers around the world, but also risked millions of dollars at the box office.
That helped this episode set a new record for viewership.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after the end of the MASH series in 1983, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. got pregnant, and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, a greedy glutton with a charismatic smile: a sly businessman and unfaithful husband who tried to have his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), an alcoholic, committed to a mental institution.
"I know what I want to have on J.R.'s headstone", Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the one thing that didn't work.
