A course exploring "the end of the world" begins
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charme decided to teach a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long count" of the Mayan calendar, which is supposed to come on December 21, was seized upon by many as evidence that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what lay ahead in the next few months: catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget collapse that some have called "debt Armageddon", and a growing conflict that is dragging Israel into the place where Christian end-of-the-world theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charme told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you analyze what's going on in the world today, like if we had 30 days left, it's a really good time.
And remember, bad means good to the apocalyptic mind.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, an academic assistant named Barry Vacker is teaching a course on "Middle Ages, Culture, and the End of the World".
Every week, students study apocalyptic topics like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We're looking at why these ideas spread over time", he says, "and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that drive certain human behaviors.
For example, if nuclear material were to fall into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, students are analyzing apocalyptic-themed movies and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, plausible and impossible", says Vacker.
On the main campus of Penn State, Matthew Restall, a professor of Latin American history, and his colleague Amara Solari, a graduate assistant in art history and anthropology, have teamed up to create a course simply called The End of the World.
"We don't connect '2012' because we always count on the possibility of re-arranging the course in case the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "imminent destruction", students must study, do projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the evening of the supposed end of the world", Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched out to two hours", said Restall of his high-performing course, which had 35 students enrolled.
Weeks and weeks before the semester started, we got emails asking if there was still room.
The students themselves assure us that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
And so, apocalyptic, secular, or religious thinking is just a matter of comfort or lack of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, said that he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I never heard of a class where that could be taught", he said.
"I'm enjoying this".
But no student interviewed, let alone the professor, said he believed in the December 21 deadline.
"Our first project was about Mayan predictions, and we're kind of refuting it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar", Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back centuries, where people respond to changes in their environment with predictions of the end of the world.
The Internet has fueled this speculation.
"That's not what people think about", he said.
It's happening in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who is teaching in the Philippines this year, was quick to respond to a question about a course there on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world", he wrote, hinting at an exception to the highest authority.
We have the Pope's mercy.
Restall noted that many doomsdays have been talked about over the years, and he said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors alike.
A few said that they were planning to attend the "end of the world" celebration.
"I'll probably call some friends to have a laugh", explained 20-year-old communication student Samira Ford.
